According to legend, when {{ill|Amaterasu|ja|天照大神}} hid inside the Heavenly Rock Cave, the assembled deities sang and danced to coax her out. Based on this tradition, a kagura performance is held before the divine presence of the Kashiko-dokoro around the time of the {{ill|Winter Solstice|ja|冬至}}.{{Sfn|Nakahiro Nakazawa|2018|p=90-91}} The ritual offerings ({{ill|Shinsen|ja|神饌}}) presented during this ceremony are on par with those of grand festivals.{{Sfn|Yasuo Ohara|1994|p=132}}

== History ==
[[File:Origin_of_Iwato_Kagura_Dance_Amaterasu_by_Toyokuni_III_(Kunisada)_1856.png|thumb|320px|''The Origins of Iwato Kagura'' (by Utagawa Toyokuni III)]]

The origins of kagura are traced to the performance of sacred dances before the rock cave where {{ill|Amaterasu|ja|天照大御神}} secluded herself, as described in the {{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記}}.{{Sfn|Makoto Nakamoto|2016|p=66-67}} 

A reference in the Nara-period Shinto text {{ill|Kogo Shūi|ja|古語拾遺}} states that the role of kagura was performed by the {{ill|Sarume no Kimi|ja|猨女君}} clan.{{Sfn|Makoto Nakamoto|2016|p=66}} The Heian-period ''{{ill|Sanuki Tenji Nikki|ja|讃岐典侍日記}}'' describes a ''Seisho-dō Mikagura'' performance in which it was remarked that "it is only natural that Amaterasu no longer remains hidden in the rock cave," reinforcing the connection between kagura and the Iwato myth.{{Sfn|Makoto Nakamoto|2016|p=68}}

Originally, kagura was performed by women, but over time, it became exclusively performed by men within the royal court.{{Sfn|Makoto Nakamoto|2016|p=68}} 

Records from the first year of {{ill|Ninna era|ja|仁和元年}} (885) in the {{ill|Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|ja|日本三代実録}} document a kagura performance held before {{ill|Emperor Kōkō|ja|光孝天皇}}.{{Sfn|Makoto Nakamoto|2016|p=76-79}} 

The first kagura established as an annual imperial court ritual was the return procession of the {{ill|Kamo Festival|ja|賀茂祭}} initiated by {{ill|Emperor Uda|ja|宇多天皇}}.{{Sfn|Makoto Nakamoto|2016|p=82-83}}

The tradition of the Naishidokoro Mikagura began in the reign of {{ill|Emperor Ichijō|ja|一条天皇}}, following a fire in the Naishidokoro in Kankō 2 (1005), which damaged the sacred mirror. The performance was conducted to appease the divine will.{{Sfn|Makoto Nakamoto|2016|p=101}} Initially performed irregularly, in Chōryaku 2 (1038), {{ill|Emperor Go-Suzaku|ja|後朱雀天皇}} decreed that it should be held annually in December.{{Sfn|Makoto Nakamoto|2016|p=101}}

During the {{ill|Nanboku-chō period|ja|南北朝時代}}, three successive Northern Court emperors ascended the throne without the Three Sacred Treasures. The kagura was performed in a "ceremony as if the mirror were present" (如在の礼).{{Sfn|Makoto Nakamoto|2021|p=71-72}} In the Southern Court, however, Emperor Go-Murakami personally led the performance before the actual sacred mirror.{{Sfn|Makoto Nakamoto|2021|p=73}}

Following the outbreak of the {{ill|Ōnin War|ja|応仁の乱}}, the emperor and retired emperor evacuated to {{ill|Muromachi Palace|ja|室町殿}}, while the Imperial Palace was occupied by {{ill|Toki Shigeyori|ja|土岐成頼}} and the Sento Imperial Palace by {{ill|Hatakeyama Yoshinari|ja|畠山義就}}, leading to the suspension of all court ceremonies.{{Sfn|Makoto Nakamoto|2021|p=34}} 

In Bunmei 2 (1470) and Bunmei 4 (1472), mysterious rumblings were heard from the Naishidokoro, interpreted as divine anger. In response, the imperial court constructed a new Naishidokoro at the southeast corner of the Muromachi Palace.{{Sfn|Makoto Nakamoto|2021|p=52}} A relocation ceremony and kagura performance were conducted on the 22nd day of the second month of Bunmei 4.{{Sfn|Makoto Nakamoto|2021|p=53-55}}

Although preparations for the Naishidokoro Mikagura were made in December of Bunmei 5, a lack of financial support from the shogunate delayed the ceremony.{{Sfn|Makoto Nakamoto|2021|p=120-121}} However, in Bunmei 6 (1474), under strong insistence from {{ill|Emperor Go-Tsuchimikado|ja|後土御門天皇}}, the performance was held, with the emperor personally attending.{{Sfn|Makoto Nakamoto|2021|p=125-129}} The court summoned underground poets {{ill|Tachūei|ja|多忠英}} and {{ill|Takuji|ja|多久時}}, overcoming significant challenges.{{Sfn|Makoto Nakamoto|2021|p=130}} It is recorded that the kagura performance was attended by nobles as well as lower-ranking officials and a large audience of men and women.{{Sfn|Makoto Nakamoto|2021|p=129}}

