The tradition of the Naishidokoro Mikagura began in the reign of {{ill|Emperor Ichijō|ja|一条天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Ichijō|qq=}}, following a fire in the Naishidokoro in Kankō 2 (1005), which damaged the sacred mirror. The performance was conducted to appease the divine will.{{Sfn|Makoto Nakamoto|2016|p=101}} Initially performed irregularly, in Chōryaku 2 (1038), {{ill|Emperor Go-Suzaku|ja|後朱雀天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Go-Suzaku|qq=}} decreed that it should be held annually in December.{{Sfn|Makoto Nakamoto|2016|p=101}}

During the {{ill|Nanboku-chō period|ja|南北朝時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nanboku-chō period|qq=}}, three successive Northern Court emperors ascended the throne without the Three Sacred Treasures. The kagura was performed in a "ceremony as if the mirror were present" (如在の礼).{{Sfn|Makoto Nakamoto|2021|p=71-72}} In the Southern Court, however, Emperor Go-Murakami personally led the performance before the actual sacred mirror.{{Sfn|Makoto Nakamoto|2021|p=73}}

Following the outbreak of the {{ill|Ōnin War|ja|応仁の乱|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōnin War|qq=}}, the emperor and retired emperor evacuated to {{ill|Muromachi Palace|ja|室町殿|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Muromachi Palace|qq=}}, while the Imperial Palace was occupied by {{ill|Toki Shigeyori|ja|土岐成頼|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toki Shigeyori|qq=}} and the Sento Imperial Palace by {{ill|Hatakeyama Yoshinari|ja|畠山義就|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hatakeyama Yoshinari|qq=}}, leading to the suspension of all court ceremonies.{{Sfn|Makoto Nakamoto|2021|p=34}} 

In Bunmei 2 (1470) and Bunmei 4 (1472), mysterious rumblings were heard from the Naishidokoro, interpreted as divine anger. In response, the imperial court constructed a new Naishidokoro at the southeast corner of the Muromachi Palace.{{Sfn|Makoto Nakamoto|2021|p=52}} A relocation ceremony and kagura performance were conducted on the 22nd day of the second month of Bunmei 4.{{Sfn|Makoto Nakamoto|2021|p=53-55}}

Although preparations for the Naishidokoro Mikagura were made in December of Bunmei 5, a lack of financial support from the shogunate delayed the ceremony.{{Sfn|Makoto Nakamoto|2021|p=120-121}} However, in Bunmei 6 (1474), under strong insistence from {{ill|Emperor Go-Tsuchimikado|ja|後土御門天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Go-Tsuchimikado|qq=}}, the performance was held, with the emperor personally attending.{{Sfn|Makoto Nakamoto|2021|p=125-129}} The court summoned underground poets {{ill|Tachūei|ja|多忠英|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tachūei|qq=}} and {{ill|Takuji|ja|多久時|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takuji|qq=}}, overcoming significant challenges.{{Sfn|Makoto Nakamoto|2021|p=130}} It is recorded that the kagura performance was attended by nobles as well as lower-Ranking officials and a large audience of men and women.{{Sfn|Makoto Nakamoto|2021|p=129}}

