<!--Kashiko Dokoro Mikagura-->

'''Kashiko-dokoro Mikagura''' (賢所御神楽) (historically known as '''Naishidokoro Mikagura''' (内侍所御神楽) before the modern era) is a {{ill|Ritual ceremonies of the Imperial Palace|ja|宮中祭祀|1=Ritual ceremonies of the Imperial Palace|lt=Ceremonies of the Japanese Imperial Palace|lt=Miyanaka ritual|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ritual ceremonies of the Imperial Palace|13=User:Immanuelle/Ritual ceremonies of the Imperial Palace|qq=}} in which a {{ill|Kagura|ja|神楽|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kagura|qq=}} performance is dedicated to the {{ill|Kashiko-dokoro|ja|賢所|1=Kashiko-dokoro|2=ja|3=賢所|4=fr|5=Kashiko-dokoro|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kashiko-dokoro|13=User:Immanuelle/Kashiko-dokoro|qq=}} (formerly the Naishidokoro) annually in mid-December.{{Sfn|Nakahiro Nakazawa|2018|p=90-91}}
{{User:Immanuelle/Ritual ceremonies of the Imperial Palace updated}}
[[File:Bugak002.jpg|thumb|150px|Jinchō-mai dance]]

Kashiko-dokoro Mikagura is said to have ancient origins, possibly dating back to the {{ill|Age of the Gods|ja|神代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Age of the Gods|qq=}}.{{Sfn|Nakahiro Nakazawa|2018|p=90}} While formally classified as a minor festival, it is considered one of the oldest Shinto rituals, possibly deriving from the {{ill|Amano-Iwato|ja|天岩戸|1=Amano-Iwato|lt=Heavenly Rock Cave|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Amano-Iwato|13=User:Immanuelle/Amano-Iwato|qq=}} myth.{{Sfn|Yasuo Ohara|1994|p=132}} 

According to legend, when {{ill|Amaterasu|ja|天照大神|1=Amaterasu|lt=Amaterasu Ōmikami|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Amaterasu|13=User:Immanuelle/Amaterasu|qq=}} hid inside the Heavenly Rock Cave, the assembled deities sang and danced to coax her out. Based on this tradition, a kagura performance is held before the divine presence of the Kashiko-dokoro around the time of the {{ill|Winter Solstice|ja|冬至|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Winter Solstice|qq=}}.{{Sfn|Nakahiro Nakazawa|2018|p=90-91}} The ritual offerings ({{ill|Shinsen|ja|神饌|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinsen|qq=}}) presented during this ceremony are on par with those of grand festivals.{{Sfn|Yasuo Ohara|1994|p=132}}

== History ==
[[File:Origin_of_Iwato_Kagura_Dance_Amaterasu_by_Toyokuni_III_(Kunisada)_1856.png|thumb|320px|''The Origins of Iwato Kagura'' (by Utagawa Toyokuni III)]]

The origins of kagura are traced to the performance of sacred dances before the rock cave where {{ill|Amaterasu|ja|天照大御神|1=Amaterasu|lt=Amaterasu Ōmikami|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Amaterasu|13=User:Immanuelle/Amaterasu|qq=}} secluded herself, as described in the {{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kojiki|qq=}}.{{Sfn|Makoto Nakamoto|2016|p=66-67}} 

A reference in the Nara-period Shinto text {{ill|Kogo Shūi|ja|古語拾遺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kogo Shūi|qq=}} states that the role of kagura was performed by the {{ill|Sarume no Kimi|ja|猨女君|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sarume no Kimi|qq=}} clan.{{Sfn|Makoto Nakamoto|2016|p=66}} The Heian-period ''{{ill|Sanuki Tenji Nikki|ja|讃岐典侍日記|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sanuki Tenji Nikki|qq=}}'' describes a ''Seisho-dō Mikagura'' performance in which it was remarked that "it is only natural that Amaterasu no longer remains hidden in the rock cave," reinforcing the connection between kagura and the Iwato myth.{{Sfn|Makoto Nakamoto|2016|p=68}}

Originally, kagura was performed by women, but over time, it became exclusively performed by men within the royal court.{{Sfn|Makoto Nakamoto|2016|p=68}} 

Records from the first year of {{ill|Ninna era|ja|仁和元年|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ninna era|qq=}} (885) in the {{ill|Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|ja|日本三代実録|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|qq=}} document a kagura performance held before {{ill|Emperor Kōkō|ja|光孝天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Kōkō|qq=}}.{{Sfn|Makoto Nakamoto|2016|p=76-79}} 

