Although preparations for the Naishidokoro Mikagura were made in December of Bunmei 5, a lack of financial support from the shogunate delayed the ceremony.{{Sfn|Makoto Nakamoto|2021|p=120-121}} However, in Bunmei 6 (1474), under strong insistence from [[:en:Emperor Go-Tsuchimikado|Emperor Go-Tsuchimikado]], the performance was held, with the emperor personally attending.{{Sfn|Makoto Nakamoto|2021|p=125-129}} The court summoned underground poets {{ill|Tachūei|ja|多忠英|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tachūei|qq=}} and {{ill|Takuji|ja|多久時|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takuji|qq=}}, overcoming significant challenges.{{Sfn|Makoto Nakamoto|2021|p=130}} It is recorded that the kagura performance was attended by nobles as well as lower-Ranking officials and a large audience of men and women.{{Sfn|Makoto Nakamoto|2021|p=129}}

